            "type": "h1-lesson",
            "content": "&#128218; &nbsp;The Präsens tense"
        },
        {
            "type": "h2-post",
            "content": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": "The <b><i>Plusquamperfekt</i></b> also known as the past perfect tense in English, is used in German to describe actions that had been completed before another action took place in the past. It provides a way to sequence events in the past, showing which action happened first."
        },
        {
            "type": "callout",
            "content": "The <i>Plusquamperfekt</i> tense in German is very easy to learn once you know the <i>Perfekt</i> tense!"
        },
        {
            "type": "h2",
            "content": "Usage"
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": "We use the <i>Plusquamperfekt</i> tense to express:"
        },
        {
            "type": "list",
            "itemsList": {
                "items": [
                    {
                        "text": "<b>Narrative past:</b> When telling a story or describing a series of events, the Plusquamperfekt is used to indicate an action that happened before another past action:",
                        "example": {
                            "audio": "Nachdem er gegessen hatte, ging er spazieren",
                            "text": "Example: Nachdem er <b>gegessen</b> hatte einen Film $__gesehen-sehen[verb-link-hover]__$ ",
                            "translation": "(After he had eaten, he went for a walk)"
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "Indicating a change of location or state:",
                        "example": {
                            "audio": "Er ist nach Berlin gefahren.",
                            "text": "Er <b>ist</b> nach Berlin $__gefahren-fahren[verb-link-hover]__$.",
                            "translation": "(He went to Berlin)"
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "Talking about an experience:",
                        "example": {
                            "audio": "Sie hat in Frankreich gelebt.",
                            "text": "Sie <b>hat</b> in Frankreich $__gelebt-leben[verb-link-hover]__$.",
                            "translation": "(She has lived in France)"
                        }
                    },
                                        {
                        "text": "Expressing a past action with a visible result:",
                        "example": {
                            "audio": "Er hat das Fenster geöffnet.",
                            "text": "Er <b>hat</b> das Fenster $__geöffnet-öffnen[verb-link-hover]__$.",
                            "translation": "(He has opened the window)"
                        }
                    }
                ]
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "h2",
            "content": "Conjugation"
        },
        {
            "type": "html",
            "content": "<p>The Perfekt tense is formed using two components:</p><ol><li>The <b data-verb-stem>auxiliary verb</b> (either <b>'haben'</b> or <b>'sein'</b>) conjugated in the <b>present tense</b>.</li><li>The <b data-verb-prefix><i>Partizip II</i></b> of the <b>main verb.</b></li>"
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "image": {
                "src": "/img/lessons/perfekt-formation.svg",
                "alt": "german Perkect tense conjugation",
                "height": 71.5,
                "width": 300
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "h3",
            "content": "Word order"
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": "In main clauses, the auxiliary verb is in the second position, and the past participle is at the end of the sentence."
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "image": {
                "src": "/img/lessons/perfekt-word-order.svg",
                "alt": "german Perkect tense conjugation",
                "height": 110,
                "width": 242
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "h3",
            "content": "Auxiliary Verbs: 'haben' and 'sein'"
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": "The auxiliary verbs used on the <i>Perfekt</i> tense are <b>haben</b> and <b>sein</b>:"
        },
        {
            "type": "list",
            "itemsList": {
                "items": [
                    {
                        "text": "<b>Haben:</b> Used with most verbs:",
                        "example": {
                            "audio": "Ich habe Gemüse gegessen.",
                            "text": "Ich <b>habe</b> Gemüse $__gegessen-essen[verb-link-hover]__$ ",
                            "translation": "(I have eaten vegetables)"
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "text": "<b>Sein:</b> Used with verbs that indicate a change of state or movement (e.g., 'gehen' - to go, 'kommen' - to come):",
                        "example": {
                            "audio": "Er ist nach Berlin gefahren.",
                            "text": "Er <b>ist</b> nach Berlin $__gefahren-fahren[verb-link-hover]__$.",
                            "translation": "(He went to Berlin)"
                        }
                    }
                ]
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "callout",
            "content": "It is very important to master the conjugations of <b>haben</b> and <b>sein</b> to learn the <i>Perfekt</i> tense:"
        },
        {
            "type": "h4",
            "content": "Sein präsens conjugation:"
        },
        {
            "type": "table",
            "table": {
                "audio": "ich bin, du bist, (er) (sie) (es) ist, wir sein, ihr sind, sie sind.",
                "headings": ["person", "sein"],
